<TITLE>Made in India review  an emotionally charged mix of politics and parenthood</TITLE>


<TEXT>
A Eva (Gina Isaac), newly <EVENT eid="e1" class="OCCURRENCE">arrived</EVENT> from the UK, has high hopes, a high-level job in advertising and a strong determination to <EVENT eid="e2" class="OCCURRENCE">do</EVENT> things her way, <TIMEX3 tid="t1" type="DURATION" value="PXY">following years</TIMEX3> of failed IVF treatments. Doctor Gupta (Syreeta Kumar) is cool, competent and in <EVENT eid="e3" class="OCCURRENCE">charge</EVENT> of a clinic so in demand from foreign clients that she is <TIMEX3 tid="t2" type="DATE" value="PRESENT_REF">now</TIMEX3> <EVENT eid="e4" class="OCCURRENCE">investing</EVENT> in an ambitious expansion programme to <EVENT eid="e5" class="OCCURRENCE">meet</EVENT> their needs. Aditi (Ulrika Krishnamurti), the intended surrogate, will <EVENT eid="e6" class="OCCURRENCE">earn</EVENT> more in <TIMEX3 tid="t3" type="DURATION" value="P9M">nine months</TIMEX3> than she could through <TIMEX3 tid="t4" type="DURATION" value="P10Y">10 years</TIMEX3> work in her village.

A dramatically potent situation is given added impetus (and conceptual complexity) when politics <EVENT eid="e7" class="OCCURRENCE">disrupt</EVENT> the personal agendas. State elections <EVENT eid="e8" class="OCCURRENCE">loom</EVENT>; a ban is <EVENT eid="e9" class="OCCURRENCE">introduced</EVENT> on foreigners paying for surrogacy in India. What follows is a revelation of the womens characters under pressure (brilliantly multifaceted performances from Isaac, Kumar and Krishnamurti), which exposes questions surrounding surrogacy (without <EVENT eid="e10" class="OCCURRENCE">offering</EVENT> glib answers) and wider economic issues (a politicians voiceover <EVENT eid="e11" class="OCCURRENCE">attacks</EVENT> the ban, claiming surrogacy <EVENT eid="e12" class="I_STATE">allows</EVENT> "produce of India" to make "wealth flow back" to the country), as well as semi-submerged, postcolonial attitudes. Places are precisely <EVENT eid="e13" class="OCCURRENCE">evoked</EVENT> and yet also flow and twine thanks to the combined effects of Prema Mehtas lighting, Arun Ghoshs sound design (also original music) and Dennos multiple screens, on to which are projected Shanaz Gulzars video images. Each element <EVENT eid="e14" class="I_STATE">enhances</EVENT> the plays competing tensions between fragmentation and cohesion, opposites tautly <EVENT eid="e15" class="OCCURRENCE">balanced</EVENT> by Katie Posners fine direction. The whole makes for an intellectually and emotionally stirring encounter.
</TEXT>


